{"parse":{"title":"Bathroom reading","pageid":58403719,"revid":858342057,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Senator_Robert_McKnight_sits_on_a_toilet_seat_dnd0276.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"A laughing man wearing a suit sits on a toilet. In front of him is a desk with papers.\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1d/Senator_Robert_McKnight_sits_on_a_toilet_seat_dnd0276.jpg/220px-Senator_Robert_McKnight_sits_on_a_toilet_seat_dnd0276.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"307\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1d/Senator_Robert_McKnight_sits_on_a_toilet_seat_dnd0276.jpg/330px-Senator_Robert_McKnight_sits_on_a_toilet_seat_dnd0276.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1d/Senator_Robert_McKnight_sits_on_a_toilet_seat_dnd0276.jpg/440px-Senator_Robert_McKnight_sits_on_a_toilet_seat_dnd0276.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"600\" data-file-height=\"837\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Senator_Robert_McKnight_sits_on_a_toilet_seat_dnd0276.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Florida Senator Robert McKnight sits on a toilet seat at his desk in the <a href=\"/wiki/Florida_Senate\" title=\"Florida Senate\">Florida Senate</a> building</div></div></div>\n<p><b>Bathroom reading</b> is the act of <a href=\"/wiki/Reading_(process)\" title=\"Reading (process)\">reading</a> text while in a <a href=\"/wiki/Bathroom\" title=\"Bathroom\">bathroom</a>, usually while sitting on the <a href=\"/wiki/Toilet\" title=\"Toilet\">toilet</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Defecation\" title=\"Defecation\">defecating</a>. The practice has been common throughout history and remains widespread today with both printed material and <a href=\"/wiki/Smartphone\" title=\"Smartphone\">smartphones</a>.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#History\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">History</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Bathroom_reading_and_literature\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Bathroom reading and literature</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Sanitation,_hygiene_and_health\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Sanitation, hygiene and health</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Bathroom_reading_and_psychology\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Bathroom reading and psychology</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#See_also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-6\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">6</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"History\">History</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Bathroom_reading&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: History\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Bathroom reading has been commonplace throughout history. <a href=\"/wiki/Ancient_Rome\" title=\"Ancient Rome\">Ancient Roman</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Thermae\" title=\"Thermae\">bath houses</a> often contained libraries with scrolls for reading.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Alford_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Alford-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Before the invention of modern <a href=\"/wiki/Toilet_paper\" title=\"Toilet paper\">toilet paper</a>, Americans in the <a href=\"/wiki/Colonial_history_of_the_United_States\" title=\"Colonial history of the United States\">colonial period</a> often used <a href=\"/wiki/Newspaper\" title=\"Newspaper\">newspaper</a> or similar printed material to wipe themselves,<sup id=\"cite_ref-Wolf_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Wolf-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> because <a href=\"/wiki/Newsprint\" title=\"Newsprint\">newsprint</a> paper is fairly soft and absorbent.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> Writing in the 18th century, the English statesman <a href=\"/wiki/Philip_Stanhope,_4th_Earl_of_Chesterfield\" title=\"Philip Stanhope, 4th Earl of Chesterfield\">Philip Stanhope, 4th Earl of Chesterfield</a> reported that he knew \"a gentleman who was so good a manager of his time that he would not even lose that small portion of it which the call of nature obliged him to pass in the necessary-house; but gradually went through all the <a href=\"/wiki/Latin_poetry\" title=\"Latin poetry\">Latin poets</a>, in those moments.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Alford_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Alford-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The advent of the <a href=\"/wiki/Smartphone\" title=\"Smartphone\">smartphone</a> is believed to have significantly increased bathroom reading. A 2009 study conducted in Israel found that a majority of adults read from their smartphones on the toilet, and a 2015 study conducted by <a href=\"/wiki/Verizon\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Verizon\">Verizon</a> found that 90% of cell phone users admitted to reading from their phones while on the toilet.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Time_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Time-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Bathroom_reading_and_literature\">Bathroom reading and literature</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Bathroom_reading&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Bathroom reading and literature\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The term \"bathroom reading\" refers to any literary material deemed suitable for casual or light reading. In 2011, the Canadian author <a href=\"/wiki/Margaret_Atwood\" title=\"Margaret Atwood\">Margaret Atwood</a> wrote:\n</p>\n<style data-mw-deduplicate=\"TemplateStyles:r856303468\">.mw-parser-output .templatequote{overflow:hidden;margin:1em 0;padding:0 40px}.mw-parser-output .templatequote .templatequotecite{line-height:1.5em;text-align:left;padding-left:1.6em;margin-top:0}</style><blockquote class=\"templatequote\"><p>Bathroom reading is a certain kind of reading\u2014episodic, but encouraging first thing in the morning. The bathroom is a place where you can go in and pretend to be doing one thing while actually you're reading. Nobody can interrupt you. Compendiums of this and that are very useful for bathroom reading: small reading packages within a larger book. You wouldn't want to read <i><a href=\"/wiki/War_and_Peace\" title=\"War and Peace\">War and Peace</a></i> in there. You'd never come out. They'd probably call the police and get the door broken down.<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p></blockquote>\n<p><a href=\"/wiki/Pulp_magazine\" title=\"Pulp magazine\">Pulp magazines</a> were associated with bathroom reading, which the film <i><a href=\"/wiki/Pulp_Fiction\" title=\"Pulp Fiction\">Pulp Fiction</a></i> references in repeated scenes of <a href=\"/wiki/John_Travolta\" title=\"John Travolta\">John Travolta</a>'s character Vincent Vega reading the pulpy <a href=\"/wiki/Spy_fiction\" title=\"Spy fiction\">spy</a> novel <i><a href=\"/wiki/Modesty_Blaise_(novel)\" title=\"Modesty Blaise (novel)\">Modesty Blaise</a></i> while sat on a toilet.<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> Bathroom reading also refers to a <a href=\"/wiki/Literary_genre\" title=\"Literary genre\">genre</a> of books containing <a href=\"/wiki/Humour\" title=\"Humour\">humor</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Trivia\" title=\"Trivia\">trivia</a>, such as the <i><a href=\"/wiki/Uncle_John%27s_Bathroom_Reader\" title=\"Uncle John&#39;s Bathroom Reader\">Uncle John's Bathroom Reader</a></i> series.<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In <a href=\"/wiki/James_Joyce\" title=\"James Joyce\">James Joyce</a>'s novel <i><a href=\"/wiki/Ulysses_(novel)\" title=\"Ulysses (novel)\">Ulysses</a></i>, the protagonist <a href=\"/wiki/Leopold_Bloom\" title=\"Leopold Bloom\">Leopold Bloom</a> reads a magazine on the toilet and then wipes himself with it.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Time_4-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Time-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span id=\"Sanitation.2C_hygiene_and_health\"></span><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Sanitation,_hygiene_and_health\">Sanitation, hygiene and health</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Bathroom_reading&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Sanitation, hygiene and health\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>According to a professor at the <a href=\"/wiki/Columbia_University_Medical_Center\" title=\"Columbia University Medical Center\">Columbia University Medical Center</a>, reading in the bathroom can potentially facilitate <a href=\"/wiki/Transmission_(medicine)\" title=\"Transmission (medicine)\">the spread of disease</a> if <a href=\"/wiki/Airborne_disease\" title=\"Airborne disease\">airborne</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Bacteria\" title=\"Bacteria\">bacteria</a> land on reading material and are transmitted to the reader; however, the activity is not a significant health concern as long as the reading environment is <a href=\"/wiki/Sanitation\" title=\"Sanitation\">sanitary</a>, the reader does not have a <a href=\"/wiki/Immunodeficiency\" title=\"Immunodeficiency\">compromised immune system</a>, and the reader practices ordinary <a href=\"/wiki/Hygiene\" title=\"Hygiene\">hygiene</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> \n</p><p>A <a href=\"/wiki/University_of_Arizona\" title=\"University of Arizona\">University of Arizona</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Microbiologist\" title=\"Microbiologist\">microbiologist</a> who researched the topic in 2002 found that bathroom reading at the workplace was not a significant hygiene risk, noting that paper is a relatively unattractive environment for bacteria and that <a href=\"/wiki/Desk\" title=\"Desk\">desk</a> areas often have more bacteria than bathrooms because they are cleaned less frequently.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Wolf_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Wolf-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Although time spent on the toilet can increase the incidence of <a href=\"/wiki/Hemorrhoid\" title=\"Hemorrhoid\">hemorrhoids</a>, a 2009 study found that bathroom readers were not more likely than non-bathroom readers to have hemorrhoids.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Time_4-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Time-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Bathroom_reading_and_psychology\">Bathroom reading and psychology</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Bathroom_reading&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Bathroom reading and psychology\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Even when people read for extended periods of time during defecation, it is rare for bathroom readers to feel <a href=\"/wiki/Disgust\" title=\"Disgust\">disgusted</a> by the smell of their own <a href=\"/wiki/Human_feces\" title=\"Human feces\">feces</a>, or even to consciously notice the smell.<sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The <a href=\"/wiki/Psychoanalysis\" title=\"Psychoanalysis\">psychoanalyst</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Otto_Fenichel\" title=\"Otto Fenichel\">Otto Fenichel</a> believed bathroom reading was an indication of <a href=\"/wiki/Early_childhood_trauma\" title=\"Early childhood trauma\">early childhood trauma</a>, writing that the activity is \"an attempt to preserve the equilibrium of <a href=\"/wiki/Id,_ego_and_super-ego\" title=\"Id, ego and super-ego\">the ego</a>; part of one's bodily substance is being lost and so fresh matter must be absorbed through the eyes.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-Time_4-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Time-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> <a href=\"/wiki/James_Strachey\" title=\"James Strachey\">James Strachey</a>, who translated <a href=\"/wiki/Sigmund_Freud\" title=\"Sigmund Freud\">Sigmund Freud</a>'s works into English, similarly noted that the activity of casual reading while defecating was essentially \"infantile\" behavior.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Time_4-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Time-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p><a href=\"/wiki/DiMassimo_Goldstein\" title=\"DiMassimo Goldstein\">DiMassimo Brand Advertising</a> once tested <a href=\"/wiki/Campaign_advertising\" title=\"Campaign advertising\">political advertising</a> in bathrooms by placing various messages about <a href=\"/wiki/George_W._Bush\" title=\"George W. Bush\">George W. Bush</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Al_Gore\" title=\"Al Gore\">Al Gore</a> in New York City public restrooms. The company's study found that 62 percent of people \"remembered the exact message\" of bathroom ads, compared to 16 percent for <a href=\"/wiki/Billboard\" title=\"Billboard\">billboard</a> advertisements.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Wolf_2-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Wolf-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Bathroom_reading&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Bathroom_sex\" title=\"Bathroom sex\">Bathroom sex</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Bathroom_reading&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist columns references-column-width\" style=\"-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em; list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-Alford-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Alford_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Alford_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a href=\"/wiki/Henry_Alford_(writer)\" title=\"Henry Alford (writer)\">Alford, Henry</a> (July 23, 2006). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/2006/07/23/books/review/23alford.html\">\"Chamber Plots\"</a>. <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_New_York_Times\" title=\"The New York Times\">The New York Times</a></i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">September 4,</span> 2018</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=The+New+York+Times&amp;rft.atitle=Chamber+Plots&amp;rft.date=2006-07-23&amp;rft.aulast=Alford&amp;rft.aufirst=Henry&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nytimes.com%2F2006%2F07%2F23%2Fbooks%2Freview%2F23alford.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ABathroom+reading\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Wolf-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Wolf_2-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Wolf_2-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Wolf_2-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">Wolf, Buck (June 4, 2002). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/WolfFiles/story?id=91568&amp;page=1\">\"Bathroom Reading: Good, Clean Fun\"</a>. <i><a href=\"/wiki/ABC_News\" title=\"ABC News\">ABC News</a></i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">September 4,</span> 2018</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=ABC+News&amp;rft.atitle=Bathroom+Reading%3A+Good%2C+Clean+Fun&amp;rft.date=2002-06-04&amp;rft.aulast=Wolf&amp;rft.aufirst=Buck&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fabcnews.go.com%2FEntertainment%2FWolfFiles%2Fstory%3Fid%3D91568%26page%3D1&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ABathroom+reading\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">Higgins, Edward (June 4, 2002). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.farmersalmanac.com/what-did-people-use-before-toilet-paper-24419\">\"What Did People Use Before Toilet Paper?\"</a>. <i><a href=\"/wiki/Farmers%27_Almanac\" title=\"Farmers&#39; Almanac\">Farmers' Almanac</a></i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">September 4,</span> 2018</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Farmers%27+Almanac&amp;rft.atitle=What+Did+People